"use strict";(self.webpackChunkchris7462_github_io=self.webpackChunkchris7462_github_io||[]).push([["6607"],{7735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/2026/05/23/pixel8-fingerprint","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2026/05/23/pixel8-fingerprint","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-23-pixel8-fingerprint/index.mdx","title":"Fix Pixel 8 Fingerprint Scanner After Screen Replacement (Linux)","description":"After replacing the screen on a Google Pixel 8, the under-display fingerprint sensor needs to be recalibrated. Google provides an official tool at pixelrepair.withgoogle.com/udfps, but it only works on Windows and macOS \u2014 and on newer firmware versions it may report \\"firmware too new\\" and refuse to run.","date":"2026-05-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Pixel","permalink":"/blog/tags/pixel","description":"Google Pixel posts"},{"inline":false,"label":"Android","permalink":"/blog/tags/android","description":"Android related posts"},{"inline":false,"label":"Linux","permalink":"/blog/tags/linux","description":"Linux tips and guides"},{"inline":false,"label":"Repair","permalink":"/blog/tags/repair","description":"Hardware repair guides"}],"readingTime":2.5,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Yi-Chen Zhang","title":"Lead Engineer, AI and Autonomous","url":"https://chris7462.github.io","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/yc"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/Chris7462","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/yi-chen-zhang-b72907116/"},"imageURL":"https://chris7462.github.io/img/profile.jpg","key":"yc"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Fix Pixel 8 Fingerprint Scanner After Screen Replacement (Linux)","date":"2026-05-23T00:00:00.000Z","authors":"yc","tags":["pixel","android","linux","repair"]},"unlisted":false},"content":"After replacing the screen on a Google Pixel 8, the under-display fingerprint sensor needs to be recalibrated. Google provides an official tool at [pixelrepair.withgoogle.com/udfps](https://pixelrepair.withgoogle.com/udfps), but it only works on Windows and macOS \u2014 and on newer firmware versions it may report \\"firmware too new\\" and refuse to run.\\n\\nThis guide documents a working method using the command line on Linux, bypassing the browser tool entirely.\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\nHere\'s what the repair looked like \u2014 the screen assembly separated from the frame, and the new screen ready to boot:\\n\\n![Opening the Pixel 8](./img/pixel8-open.jpeg)\\n\\n![Screen separated from frame](./img/pixel8-separated.jpeg)\\n\\nAfter reassembly, the new screen boots up but the fingerprint sensor needs recalibration:\\n\\n![New screen booting up with calibration notice](./img/pixel8-newscreen.jpeg)\\n\\n## Requirements\\n\\n- Linux computer (tested on Ubuntu 24.04)\\n- USB-C cable \u2014 use the best quality cable you have (this matters)\\n- `fastboot` installed on your computer\\n- Google Pixel 8 with a newly replaced screen\\n\\n## Steps\\n\\n### 1. Enable USB Debugging on the phone\\n\\nGo to **Settings \u2192 About phone** and tap **Build number** 7 times to enable Developer Options. Then go to **Settings \u2192 System \u2192 Developer Options** and enable **USB Debugging**.\\n\\n### 2. Install fastboot\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo apt install fastboot -y\\n```\\n\\n### 3. Boot into Fastboot Mode\\n\\nPower off the phone, then hold **Power + Volume Down** until you see the Fastboot screen. Do not select Rescue Mode or any other option \u2014 stay on the main Fastboot screen.\\n\\n### 4. Connect and verify\\n\\nPlug the phone into your computer and run:\\n\\n```bash\\nfastboot devices\\n```\\n\\nYou should see your device serial number listed. If nothing appears, try a different USB port or cable.\\n\\n### 5. Get the calibration file URL\\n\\n```bash\\nfastboot oem udfps get-cal-url\\n```\\n\\nThis returns a URL unique to your device, for example:\\n\\n```\\n(bootloader) https://storage.googleapis.com/hardware-mfg-data-ext-sacal/xxxxxx.signed.cal\\n```\\n\\n### 6. Download the calibration file\\n\\n```bash\\nwget <URL from previous step>\\n```\\n\\n### 7. Upload and apply the calibration\\n\\n```bash\\nfastboot stage <filename>.signed.cal\\nfastboot oem udfps update-cal\\n```\\n\\nYou should see:\\n\\n```\\n(bootloader) signature validation:passed\\nOKAY\\n```\\n\\n### 8. Reboot\\n\\n```bash\\nfastboot reboot\\n```\\n\\nAfter the phone boots, go to **Settings \u2192 Security \u2192 Fingerprint Unlock** and re-register your fingerprints.\\n\\n## Why this works\\n\\nGoogle\'s browser-based repair tool uses WebUSB, which has permission restrictions on Linux for Fastboot devices. The `fastboot oem udfps` commands communicate directly with the bootloader, bypassing the browser entirely. The calibration file is device-specific and cryptographically signed by Google, which is why `get-cal-url` is needed to fetch the correct one for your unit.\\n\\n## Troubleshooting\\n\\n**`fastboot devices` returns nothing**\\nUse a USB 2.0 port \u2014 this guide was tested on USB 2.0 and confirmed working. USB 3.0 was not tested. Also try a higher quality cable if the device isn\'t detected.\\n\\n**`signature validation: failed`**\\nThe calibration file doesn\'t match your device. Make sure you used the URL returned by `get-cal-url` for your specific phone \u2014 don\'t reuse a file from another device.\\n\\n**Fingerprint still not working after reboot**\\nReboot one more time manually after setting up your fingerprint."}]}}')}}]);